conflict.

41:24.182 --> 41:28.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The underlying
question
also is, I guess, one of trust.

41:28.519 --> 41:34.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is just -- you have said
that, for example,
when you found out that the
Snowden revelations

41:34.092 --> 41:37.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were going to happen, that it
was going to
uncover the information
collection program

41:37.729 --> 41:41.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that you helped set up at the
NSA, that, on
a personal level, you felt that
there was

41:41.999 --> 41:42.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a betrayal of trust.

41:42.934 --> 41:44.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GEN. MICHAEL HAYDEN: Right.

41:44.736 --> 41:47.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You can
understand then
how perhaps the country would
feel betrayed

41:47.438 --> 41:50.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that one of our liberties was
being taken
away by our own government.

41:50.675 --> 41:55.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEN. MICHAEL HAYDEN: If I'm out
there working
for an agency, and if I have got
the president

41:55.546 --> 42:00.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to authorize it, and Congress to
legislate
it or oversee it, and the courts
to perform

42:00.952 --> 42:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their functions when the law
requires, I think
I have got the Madisonian
trifecta. This is

42:05.723 --> 42:09.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really important. The political
culture has
shifted underneath us, all
right?

42:09.994 --> 42:14.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a lot of good Americans, not
just ones
wearing tinfoil on their heads,
if you understand

42:14.165 --> 42:18.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what I mean, very serious,
thinking Americans
are now looking at that and
saying, in today's

42:19.003 --> 42:23.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
political culture, what you just
described,
Hayden, is no longer consent of
the governed.

42:23.908 --> 42:28.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That is consent of the
governors. You may
have told them, but you didn't
tell me.

42:28.813 --> 42:35.286 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, now we have what is
unarguably an existential
question for American espionage.
How will

42:35.319 --> 42:41.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we be able to conduct espionage
in the future,
inside a broader political
culture that demands

42:41.092 --> 42:46.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more transparency and more
public accountability
from every aspect of national
life?

42:46.531 --> 42:53.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is a fundamental question.
And one final
point. We, the spy guys, have to
accommodate

42:53.971 --> 42:56.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to the broader political
culture, not the
other way around.

42:56.674 --> 42:58.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: General
Michael Hayden.

42:58.309 --> 43:00.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The book is called "Playing to
the Edge."

43:00.178 --> 43:01.979 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thanks so much for joining us.

43:02.013 --> 43:08.686 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GEN. MICHAEL HAYDEN: Thank you.

43:08.719 --> 43:15.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Now to another
reignited debate,
this one about the role and size
of the country's

43:15.726 --> 43:18.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
big banks, Wall Street, and
accountability.

43:18.963 --> 43:22.934 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's been playing out
periodically in the
presidential campaign, and is
once again a

43:22.967 --> 43:26.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
subject of attention and debate
in the world
of finance.

43:26.204 --> 43:30.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, we start a series of
occasional conversations
on the subject.

43:30.541 --> 43:32.376 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our first.

43:32.410 --> 43:36.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Last week came a
strong argument
that -- quote -- "The biggest
banks continue

43:36.681 --> 43:39.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to pose a significant, ongoing
risk to our
economy."

43:40.017 --> 43:42.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it came from an unusual
source.

43:42.453 --> 43:47.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Neel Kashkari is a former
investment banker.
He started his career at Goldman
Sachs, then

43:47.124 --> 43:52.263 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
joined the Bush Treasury
Department in 2006,
later serving as a key player in
the government's

43:52.296 --> 43:57.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
response to the financial crisis
as administrator
of the TARP program, which
helped bail out

43:57.101 --> 43:58.803 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the big banks.

43:58.836 --> 44:03.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2014, he ran for governor of
California
as a Republican, losing to
incumbent Jerry

44:03.307 --> 44:08.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Brown. He's now president of the
Federal Reserve
Bank of Minneapolis, and joins
us now.

44:08.312 --> 44:10.047 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you.

44:10.081 --> 44:14.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, still too big to fail,
you're saying.
This is in spite of Dodd-Frank,
in spite of

44:14.151 --> 44:18.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all we have seen. You are
suggesting a crisis
could still happen and big banks
would still

44:18.856 --> 44:20.691 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
need bailing out?

44:20.725 --> 44:22.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEEL KASHKARI, President,
Federal Reserve
Bank of Minneapolis: Yes.
Unfortunately, that's

44:22.360 --> 44:24.161 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
true.

44:24.195 --> 44:26.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dodd-Frank has made a lot of
progress. The
banks are stronger. They have
more capital,

44:26.998 --> 44:31.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so they can withstand bad things
happening.
But if something -- if a big
shock were to

44:31.602 --> 44:35.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hit the U.S. economy, I'm afraid
that the
taxpayers would likely still
have to step

44:35.740 --> 44:37.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in and bail out the banks.

44:37.909 --> 44:42.580 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In my view, based on my
experience during
the crisis, we have not yet
solved the too-big-to-fail

44:42.613 --> 44:44.382 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
problem. And we do need to.

44:44.415 --> 44:47.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And so things
like the stress
test, you have already had some
people push

44:47.518 --> 44:52.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
back at your critique, stress
test and others
things. You're just -- you don't
think those

44:52.223 --> 44:54.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are strong enough; you don't
trust them?

44:54.258 --> 44:56.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NEEL KASHKARI: Well, here's the
thing.

44:56.460 --> 45:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The crisis in 2008 was so
devastating for
the U.S. economy, millions of
jobs were lost,

45:02.199 --> 45:06.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tens of trillions of dollars of
wealth was
destroyed by that terrible
crisis. I think

45:06.504 --> 45:09.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we all agree that we never want
to have that
happen again.

45:09.307 --> 45:13.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we need to be able to allow
banks to run
into trouble without bringing
down the whole

45:13.744 --> 45:19.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. economy. If you remember
the tech bubble
in the 1990s, it was a big boom
and then it

45:19.717 --> 45:24.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crashed. That was painful for
Silicon Valley,
but it didn't risk the whole
U.S. economy.

45:24.121 --> 45:27.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We need to make sure our
financial system
is that strong, so that it can
withstand the

45:27.858 --> 45:29.927 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
shock without hurting the rest
of us.

45:29.961 --> 45:36.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Just to be clear,
how serious
or how dire is the situation? Is
the financial

45:36.033 --> 45:39.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
system at risk now? Is that what
you are suggesting?

45:39.403 --> 45:44.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEEL KASHKARI: No, I think the
financial system
is strong right now. But the key
is, now is

45:44.141 --> 45:49.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the time, when it's strong, for
us to make
these big transformational
changes, so that

45:49.280 --> 45:53.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
10 years from now or 20 or 30
years from now,
we don't have another crisis.

45:53.651 --> 45:57.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, as a society, we tend
to repeat
the same mistakes. A lot of
mistakes that

45:57.722 --> 46:02.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
led to the Great Depression, we
repeated in
2000 -- in the 2000s, leading to
the great

46:02.326 --> 46:06.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crash. And so we need to make
sure that we
make the changes now, so that 20
or 30 years

46:07.031 --> 46:08.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from now, we're not back in the
same situation.

46:09.000 --> 46:12.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, in the
options that you
laid out in a speech last week,
option number

46:12.470 --> 46:16.073 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
one was break -- was the
straightforward break
up the big banks.

46:16.107 --> 46:22.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, how would you do that? How
do you decide
what is big? And why, for
example, would 10

46:22.780 --> 46:26.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
moderate-sized banks be less
dangerous than
five big ones?

46:26.817 --> 46:28.552 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NEEL KASHKARI: Sure.

46:28.586 --> 46:31.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, what we're doing in
Minneapolis is,
we're bringing experts together
from around

46:31.589 --> 46:35.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the country who have different
proposals for
how to solve too big to fail.
So, we haven't

46:35.760 --> 46:40.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
picked which one we think is
best yet. We
want to bring the experts in,
analyze their

46:40.331 --> 46:43.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
proposals, and come out with our
recommendations
at the end of the year.

46:43.501 --> 46:48.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But look at the -- in the 1980s,
roughly 1,000
Savings &amp; Loans failed in the
S&amp;L crisis.

46:48.906 --> 46:53.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, that was devastating for
those communities
and for those banks, but it
didn't risk an

46:53.644 --> 46:59.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
entire nationwide economic
collapse. So, there
is a precedent of having smaller
banks, they

46:59.850 --> 47:03.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
might make similar mistakes
without bringing
down the whole economy.

47:03.554 --> 47:07.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We want to analyze these
objectively and figure
out what's the right solution
and how do we

47:07.792 --> 47:09.694 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
go forward.

47:09.727 --> 47:12.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: As you know, a
number of bankers
in the past and even after you
gave your talk,

47:12.897 --> 47:17.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they have said that bigger is in
some ways
better, right, that they can
offer more services,

47:17.234 --> 47:22.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that if U.S. banks were not
allowed to be
so big, international banks,
China and elsewhere,

47:22.073 --> 47:24.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
would swoop in and take the
business.

47:24.041 --> 47:28.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEEL KASHKARI: Well, you know,
if other countries
want to take huge risks with
their financial

47:28.646 --> 47:33.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
systems, we can't stop them. My
view is, we
should do what's right for the
United States,

47:33.551 --> 47:37.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
come up with one set of rules
for any bank
that wants to do business here,
and then enforce

47:37.688 --> 47:39.457 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
those rules evenly.

47:39.490 --> 47:44.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, hopefully, we can lead the
rest of the
world to follow our path, follow
our example.

47:44.395 --> 47:48.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need to address this. It's
not only American
banks that are too big to fail.
As you indicated,

47:48.699 --> 47:52.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there are some banks outside the
U.S. too.
But it's time for us to show
leadership on

47:52.503 --> 47:54.371 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this issue.

47:54.405 --> 47:58.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I read your
speech. You did
not suggest or propose bringing
back Glass-Steagall.

47:58.576 --> 48:04.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I wonder why not. Why not go
farther to once
again separate commercial
banking from investment

48:04.482 --> 48:06.283 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
banking?

48:06.317 --> 48:09.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEEL KASHKARI: You know, I don't
have a strong
opposition to bringing back
Glass-Steagall.

48:09.954 --> 48:14.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I just know, based on the crisis
that we just
went through, it really wasn't
the combination

48:14.258 --> 48:18.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of investment banking and
commercial banking
that triggered that crisis. It
was the fact

48:18.462 --> 48:23.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that a lot of banks made a lot
of bad loans.
It was plain vanilla lending
that went off

48:23.801 --> 48:25.603 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
course.

48:25.636 --> 48:28.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we need to make sure our
banking system
and non-banks, our insurance
companies, et

48:28.973 --> 48:32.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cetera, that they are all safe
and secure
and that they can't risk
bringing down the

48:32.710 --> 48:34.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
whole U.S. economy.

48:34.512 --> 48:39.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you know, in 2008, AIG, one
of the largest
insurance companies, that became
a systemic

48:39.583 --> 48:44.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
risk that almost brought us
down, and it required
a taxpayer bailout. I think we
all agree we

48:44.355 --> 48:46.123 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
never want to do that again.

48:46.157 --> 48:49.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm proposing, let's take
action now to
make sure we're never in that
situation.

48:49.393 --> 48:53.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And let me just
ask you, when
you made this speech and got a
lot of attention

48:54.031 --> 48:59.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
last week, a lot of the focus
was on the messenger,
an unlikely messenger, a lot of
people thought,

48:59.270 --> 49:04.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a former banker now telling us
the banks are
too big, a former regulator
telling us that

49:04.375 --> 49:10.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
essentially regulators are not
able, even
now, to act in a way that still
might hurt

49:10.581 --> 49:13.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the economy, still might have to
bail out
the banks.

49:13.884 --> 49:18.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A reformed -- a reform person,
what -- how
do you describe yourself? How
are we to see

49:18.856 --> 49:19.890 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
this?

49:19.924 --> 49:22.059 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NEEL KASHKARI: Well, I am an
experienced person.

49:22.092 --> 49:27.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was a strong free market
ideologue going
into Washington. Then we all
lived through

49:27.765 --> 49:32.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the terrible economic crisis.
And I think
I learned humility about markets
can make

49:32.870 --> 49:35.005 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mistakes. Regulators are not
omniscient.

49:35.039 --> 49:40.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I asked people, I said, did you
predict that
the price of oil would drop from
$150 to $30?

49:40.477 --> 49:44.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I didn't see it. There are a lot
of things
that can happen in the world
economy that

49:44.381 --> 49:47.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we're not going to be able to
predict. So,
we need to make sure that our
financial system

49:47.952 --> 49:53.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is robust, so that if those
things happen,
the system can be strong and not
require taxpayer

49:53.190 --> 49:56.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
bailouts, and not cause
devastation to the
American people.

49:56.293 --> 49:59.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Neel Kashkari,
thank you so
much.

49:59.196 --> 50:04.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NEEL KASHKARI: Thanks for having
me.

50:04.235 --> 50:15.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Tune in later
tonight on PBS for
a documentary focusing on the
massive amount

50:15.746 --> 50:19.049 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of digital data that we record
every day.

50:19.083 --> 50:24.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The human face of big data looks
at the indelible
digital trail we all leave
behind and explores

50:24.955 --> 50:30.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how it can be used to address
some of our
biggest challenges, hunger,
pollution, disaster

50:30.427 --> 50:36.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
response and health. But it
turns out it can
also help us understand how
babies learn words.

50:36.400 --> 50:43.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEB ROY, MIT: At MIT, Deb Roy
and his colleagues
wanted to see if they could
understand how

50:43.507 --> 50:46.977 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
children acquire language.

50:47.011 --> 50:51.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we realized that no one
really knew, for
a simple reason. There was no
data.

50:51.148 --> 50:55.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: After he and his wife,
Rupal, brought
their newborn son home from the
hospital,

50:55.753 --> 50:59.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they did what every parent would
do, mount
a camera in the ceiling of each
room in their

50:59.990 --> 51:05.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
home and record every moment of
their lives
for two years, a mere 200
gigabytes of data

51:05.596 --> 51:07.564 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
recorded every day.

51:07.598 --> 51:15.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DEB ROY: We ended up
transcribing somewhere
between eight and nine million
words of speech.

51:15.306 --> 51:23.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as soon as we had that, we
could go and
identify the exact moment where
my son first

51:23.113 --> 51:34.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
said a new word. We started
calling them births.
We took this idea of a word
birth, and we

51:34.091 --> 51:39.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
started thinking about, why
don't we trace
back in time and look at the
gestation period

